I wanted to share some thoughts that I have had while performing recently…when ballet (and life’s) difficulties distract me and hold me back from embracing the moment.

For quite some time, I have been in a desperate struggle between my love for ballet’s ability to transcend impurity and my hate of the ugliness it can serve. I discredited it yet idolized it at the same time. The truth is that I love ballet BECAUSE I love dancing BECAUSE being moved by the connection between God, life, and the soul is an endless inspiration. 

…but to be even more honest, going onstage sometimes (for whatever reasons) terrifies me and keeps me from feeling free. So, whether I love or hate the world that becomes ballet, ultimately, I am thankful simply for the MANY moments that my personal attempt at the art of ballet has humbled me. 

Before walking onstage and as I walk off, I am always reminded of my weaknesses (not that I need much reminding). The idea of a perfect finished product is a giant that looms over me and brings me to the end of my abilities and confidence. However, the pressure and vulnerability that ballet creates in me has forced me closer to my faith. I always have the option of cowering before the giant that tells me I am not worthy, or looking higher at a towering cross where all my imperfections and fears are covered in grace no matter how worthy I am. That grace is like an ocean, and underneath those waves, I disappear in immense love…and nothing else matters. My pride dies, and gratitude comes alive. My hope shifts from the hope of personal glory to, instead, the hope that the Lord alone is glorified. You can’t and don’t need to earn God’s love; it is yours. At the end of the day, my undeserved reward is the Lord, not a good performance.

So, if you are facing a giant of any kind, don’t give inhibitions, judgements, and expectations that produce fear, insecurity, and shallow hopes any power. Instead, look higher, stand up, and dance humbly (and gratefully) through the unknown. There you will find some freedom.
#mañanas en #lasierra de #madrid #españa

May you find peace in the uncertainty of your journey and gratitude in every finite moment. May you understand that happiness is not a destination, nor can it be the only component of life…because without sadness, we cannot perceive its opposite. A path without roughness and smoothness, shadows and light, shame and contentment, will never be. Let’s hope, not expect—with the contour that paints our lives.
#happynewyear2023

I wanted to share some words by Heather Harrington in her article, “Consumer dance identity: the intersection between competition dance, televised dance shows and social media”, which I highly recommend as a read! She talks about the current media, approval, and capitalism driven culture of dance and how “[d]ance is being taught to produce a number-one finish since this will bring in new dance customers who want to be winners and famous. [T]he dancer is there to please [judges] and has paid to be there in the hopes that the identity of being a ‘good’ dancer can be validated. This body seeks approval through scores…[T]he focus is outwards towards the image in the mirror, emphasizing how the movement looks and not how it feels. Body dysmorphia and a disconnection from the self can occur in the pursuit to become America’s top dancer because the person is focused on embodying the accepted prototype that wins. The mirror is the teacher and the judge…All the emphasis on the external creates a body that does not feel, sense, or breathe…Only the end result, not the process, is valued. In this product driven push, self-discovery, experimentation, ownership, and creativity is lost…The dancer loses their sense of self, and has only learned to copy and mirror movement, not create it.” 

Perhaps, we could take a second look at what we are promoting and identifying with through the art of dance.

Today wasn’t the smoothest travel day, and I realized how privileged and impatient I am. To turn my unfathomable thoughts to the countless lives that never lived long enough to travel or work in a field they love, that never experienced more of love and life is a wake up call… The freedom to simply work, live, and love, no matter lost luggage or flight delays, is a gift. There are far too many empty places where lives should have been… Live yours gratefully.

Competitions, in my opinion, are only relevant because they provide a bit of performing experience which teaches students how to handle nerves and different conditions onstage and off. Competitions should be productive offering classes, scholarships, and even professional contracts. Kids, don’t get caught up in the points and the medals. If you do compete, remember that the judgement and comparison is not what dance is about. Dance is about artistry which you should strive to develop long after the #competition is over.

Prioritizing health (and having the perspective to do so) is tough for us dancers because we have such an overwhelming love for our art. For me, circumstances have shouted loud enough for me to hear and I will not perform tomorrow. I am, of course, disappointed to miss the opportunity to dance with @ryokato0806 who is a dream partner. Expressing my admiration for the rehearsal directors (Amy Fote, Ian Casady, Chris Coomer, and Steven Woodgate) will always be insufficient to measure up to their discipline, generosity, and expertise. The dancers…well…I love you all. Thanks to everyone @houstonballet for a wonderful experience. If you have tickets for Swan Lake tomorrow (Sunday), you will see @86sooyoun who is a gorgeous ballerina. Enjoy the inspiring production. I’ll be back onstage in no time!

It’s Sunday, a day that many people are off to religious services. I was originally planning to dance Swan Lake. Looking back at all the striving over the years in a dance world that can thanklessly expect perfection under disabling scenarios, never did adapting to unrealistic standards or appeasing expectations lead me to who I am. The truth is that I have found my richest identity through moments of honest expression. When I was a teenager, I used to choreograph and dance at my church in Canandaigua, NY, and that was always very humbling and meaningful to me, as nerdy as it sounds;) What I have learned is that no matter the embellishments or seating capacity, a theater is nothing more than my little church back home. So, today, I was supposed to bring you Odette/Odile, but instead I share with you a special, simple piece of myself. This particular solo wasn’t complicated and isn’t about the steps. I love this memory because @threegirlmama (Stephanie LaBarge) was singing. 😌 Her voice (and her character) was and is so inspiring to me. Together, we were only two women worshiping something we believe is much greater than talents or accomplishments. I can say that I have surely failed many times in life, am far from “good,” and have lost myself often. Still, I hope to always find my way back to this altar. 

Song: “Give Me Jesus” by Fernando Ortega

Posted @withregram • @saint_sauveur_festival 2/6 Les étoiles de la danse arrivent cet été à Saint-Sauveur! La Soirée des étoiles présente le gratin mondial de la danse dans un feu d’artifice de solos et de pas de deux des répertoires classique, néoclassique et contemporain. Cette semaine, on vous présente les artistes invités!

🌟Sarah Lane - « Le ballet m'a toujours emmenée dans un autre monde sur le plan artistique et spirituel », affirme l'artiste indépendante Sarah Lane. Née à San Francisco, elle fut longtemps danseuse principale à l'American Ballet Theatre, s'illustrant dans plusieurs rôles difficiles. Sa parfaite maîtrise d'Odile/Odette dans Le lac des cygnes l’amena à servir de doublure pour certaines scènes de danse de l’actrice Natalie Portman dans le film Black Swan.

🌟Derek Dunn - C’est pour faire comme sa sœur aînée que Derek Dunn a voulu suivre des cours de danse, découvrant ainsi une vocation insoupçonnée. Né au Maryland, il a reçu sa formation à Philadelphie et est passé par le Houston Ballet avant de rejoindre le Boston Ballet à titre de premier danseur. Il a remporté nombre de récompenses, dont le Youth America Grand Prix en 2008.

La soirée des étoiles
📅Représentation - Samedi 5 août et dimanche 6 août 2023, 20 h
🎪Lieu - Grand chapiteau, 167 rue Principale, Saint-Sauveur
🎫Billets : festivaldesarts.ca

Repost • @ballet.ri SARAH LANE, NEW SCHOOL DIRECTOR //

 🎉 Ballet RI is pleased to announce world-renowned dancer, teacher, coach and rehearsal director Sarah Lane will become the next Director of the School of Ballet RI, taking on a major artistic role as the leading dance educator at the organization. 

Lane, a former principal dancer with American Ballet Theater, has performed extensively as an international guest artist with ballet companies around the world. 

She will take on the role of School Director overseeing the education arm of the leading dance institution in the region, with more than 350 enrolled students annually, more than 70 scheduled weekly classes during the academic year, and 25 faculty members with a broad range of styles and backgrounds. 

Lane will begin September 1, 2023, prior to the start of fall classes. 

Link in bio for full press release.

In the summer of 2020, @sarahlaneofficial quietly departed American Ballet Theatre and leapt into the world of freelancing. The move shocked many; during her 18 years at ABT, Lane had acquired a devoted fanbase in New York City and beyond. She managed to stay busy—and even thrive—throughout the remainder of the pandemic as an online ballet teacher and guest artist at in-person classes.

Now, after three years of juggling a jam-packed schedule, including studying for a fine arts degree, working as an integrative-nutrition health coach, and being a guest rehearsal director, ballerina, and teacher, Lane is ready to step into her newest role: director of the @schoolofballet.ri (@ballet.ri).

Learn about Lane’s plans for the upcoming year, her teaching philosophy, how equity starts with education, and more at the link in our bio. 💚

#fbf Sarasota 2011 • #blackswan pas de deux rehearsal with Jose Manuel Carreño coached by Loipa Araújo. I remember being stressed about the fouettés because they weren’t strong in this run and the floor was basically concrete. Jose said, “Sarah, you need to breathe, especially in your bows, and use your plié.” Simple, wise words from a pro which have helped me ever since.

Studio Clip 2014 • I don’t think there is a #ballet that I have more of a love/hate relationship with than #themeandvariations … My love is so deep for this #balanchine masterpiece—the precision, the energy. I have practiced these steps tirelessly in my career and worked with the most dazzling coaches like Gelsey Kirkland, @susanjaffeofficial and Amanda McKerrow. All the emotions and facets culminate in a fleeting moment of such transcendental music: hope, expectation, disappointment, relief, joy, anxiety, fear, overwhelm, pain, exhaustion, frustration, passion, perfectionism, freedom, exhilaration, adoration, sensitivity, softness, agility, elegance, grace, lyricism, punctuality, unity, understanding, gratitude…in one cord, in the stillness, in the simplicity of fifth, in a sweeping gaze over the theater with a single hand of support…and then it’s over. Love has many variations but that is the only theme that gets a #ballerina through this and many other challenging, legendary ballets. #memories #abt2014

Sarah Lane began her dance training in Memphis, Tennessee at the Memphis Classical Ballet and later at the Draper Center for Dance Education in Rochester, New York. She joined American Ballet Theatre’s Studio Company in 2002, joining the main company as an apprentice in 2003 and the corps de ballet in April 2004. She rose to soloist in 2007 and principal in 2017, dancing principal roles in Manon, Giselle, Swan Lake, La Bayadère, Coppélia, Le Corsaire, Don Quixote, The Sleeping Beauty, Theme and Variations, and Whipped Cream, among others. Lane has performed as an international guest artist with Houston Ballet, San Francisco Ballet, Richmond Ballet, Teatro dell’ Opera di Roma, Kremlin Ballet, Barcelona Ballet, NBA Ballet Company and Hong Kong Ballet. Lane is also an international guest ballet teacher and an Integrative Nutrition Health Coach. She has worked as a guest rehearsal director for American Repertory Ballet and as the Director of the School of Ballet RI.

BUT in all seriousness, I have never shared much about my teacher Timothy Draper, who passed about a year after this video. He founded @draper_center and gave me opportunities to work with incredible coaches like Fiona Fairrie @fairrieballettraining , Sasha Yapparov, and Eva Evdokimova. Tim was a taskmaster; he was stern and strict. As the years went on in my training, I saw that, underneath that hard shell, he was protective, nurturing, and ever so caring. He tried not to let his soft side show, but he let his guard down on the rarest occasion only to balance my harsh self-criticism. A good teacher knows when to be firm and when to be delicate because, as teachers, we are working to cultivate artists who also know how to balance strength with fragility rather than creating conveyer belt machines. 

Tim lives on in the hearts and careers of his students and through @jameyleverett who is tending the school with unending commitment, intelligence, and ardent care. Huge CONGRATS to them on their new facility @jccrochester 🌟

P.S. I did get the chance to dance as a presidential scholar in the arts awarded by @youngarts at the Kennedy Center first in 2002. @kennedycenter went on to be my favorite theater next to the Met to perform in over the years with ABT.
